<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-453-162  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 453 162.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  May 14 1990 v9 n10 p16(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Presentation Manager under OS/2 encourages lengthy name-calling.andO;(Power User) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCormick, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   World Software Corp. (products).andO;Product:   OS/2 Presentation Manager (Graphical user interface) (usage)OS/2 2.0 (Operating system) (usage)Extend-A-Name (File management software) (usage).andO;Topic:     File ManagementProcessor Speed.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Presentation Manager Under OS/2 Encourages Lengthy Name-CallingandM;Although the new three-dimensional and icon-oriented look of PresentationManager is the most apparent change, several more-fundamental changes affectthe way software will work under OS/2 Version 2.andM;The most important of these is the HPFS or High-Performance File System, areplacement for the old MS-DOS File Allocation Table, or FAT.andM;Installing HPFS option requires you to reformat the hard disk, so you won'twant to do that unless you really need its features.andP;  But if you are using ahigh-capacity hard drive, with lots of files, then the ability to use longand more meaningful filenames becomes important.andM;Of course, you don't have to go with OS/2's HPFS to get long filenames.andP;  The$89 Extend-a-Name TSR utility from World Software Corp. of Ridgewood, N.J.,andO;allows users to append descriptions of up to 60 characters to MS-DOSfilenames.andM;That utility program is useful and provides the equivalent of an extendednaming capability for MS-DOS users.andP;  But the HPFS does far more than justbypass the old eight-character name limitation, stretching it to a maximum of256 characters.andM;HPFS is fast because it distributes the file information across the disk,rather than in a single table, and because the file and directory informationis loaded into a cache for high-speed access.andM;Especially interesting parts of the HPFS are the Extended and StandardExtended Attributesk, which are sub-files up to 64K in size containingsupplemental information about the HPFS files.andM;Why is such a large supplementary file useful or even needed?andM;Simple; HPFS files can reportedly be up to 2 gigabytes.andP;  I wasn't able toconfirm this because my largest hard drive is 1.2 gigabytes.andP;  Applicationsneed to have the ability to append some extra information about these largerfiles that can be accessed without loading in the actual file.andM;Getting Your WishandM;Another obvious use for the extended attributes is providing the ability toclick on a data filename and have the appropriate application program executeand load the file.andM;Those who have been clamoring for larger hard-disk partitions also havegotten their wish with HPFS.andP;  Disks formatted with this option can havesingle disk volumes up to 2,000 gigabytes in size.andP;  Imagine doing a TREE/F onone of those disks.andM;Other features of the new OS/2 include a Presentation Manager version ofFDisk, improved PM graphics with better use of icons, and a dual boot option,which lets you boot either MS-DOS or OS/2 without third-party utilitysoftware.andM;Performance of this version of OS/2 is markedly better.andM;John McCormick, a free-lance writer and computer consultant, has been workingwith computers since the early 1960s.andP;  He welcomes mail from readers.andP;  Writeto him care of Government Computer News, 8601 Georgia Ave., Suite 300, SilverSpring, Md.andP;  20910.andO;</TEXT></DOC>